 "Fascinating"}, {"count": 608, "id": 8, "name": "Informative"}, {"count": 28, "id": 11, "name": "Longwinded"}, {"count": 109, "id": 24, "name": "Persuasive"}, {"count": 66, "id": 1, "name": "Beautiful"}, {"count": 44, "id": 21, "name": "Unconvincing"}, {"count": 106, "id": 25, "name": "OK"}, {"count": 132, "id": 23, "name": "Jaw-dropping"}, {"count": 45, "id": 3, "name": "Courageous"}, {"count": 2, "id": 26, "name": "Obnoxious"}, {"count": 46, "id": 2, "name": "Confusing"}, {"count": 13, "id": 7, "name": "Funny"}], "speakers": [{"description": "Neuroscientist", "firstname": "Mariano", "title": "", "lastname": "Sigman", "middleinitial": "", "whylisten": "<p>Mariano Sigman, a physicist by training, is a leading figure in the cognitive neuroscience of learning and decision making. He is the founder of the Integrative Neuroscience Laboratory at the University of Buenos Aires. Sigman was awarded a Human Frontiers Career Development Award, the National Prize of Physics, the Young Investigator Prize of &quot;College de France,&quot; the IBM Scalable Data Analytics Award and is a scholar of the James S. McDonnell Foundation. In 2016 he was made a Laureate of the Pontifical Academy of Sciences.</p>  <p>In <em>The Secret Life of the Mind</em>, Sigman&rsquo;s ambition is to explain the mind so that we can understand ourselves and others more deeply. He shows how we form ideas during our first days of life, how we give shape to our fundamental decisions, how we dream and imagine, why we feel certain emotions, how the brain transforms and how who we are changes with it. Spanning biology, physics, mathematics, psychology, anthropology, linguistics, philosophy and medicine, as well as gastronomy, magic, music, chess, literature and art, The Secret Life of the Mind revolutionizes how neuroscience serves us in our lives, revealing how the infinity of neurons inside our brains manufacture how we perceive, reason, feel, dream and communicate.</p>", "slug": "mariano_sigman", "whotheyare": "In his provocative, mind-bending book \\"The Secret Life of the Mind,\\" neurologist Mariano Sigman reveals his life\\u2019s work exploring the inner workings of the human brain.", "whatotherssay": "Neuroscience has removed some of the opacity of human thought ... raising, to some extent, the curtain.", "id": 2376, "photo_url": "https://pe.tedcdn.com/images/ted/21a1b23e3429e7bfce1efb26838458c90717d53b_254x191.jpg"}], "title": "Your words may predict your future mental health", "take_action": [], "comments": 27128, "more_resources": [{"status": "approved", "start_at": null, "headline": "Automated analysis of free speech predicts psychosis onset in high-risk youths", "link_url": "http://www.nature.com/articles/npjschz201530", "eyebrow": null, "end_at": null, "image_url": "", "published": true, "visible_url": "nature.com", "type": "external_website", "blurb": "In this study published in *Nature*, Mariano Sigman and other researchers aimed to test automated speech analyses combined with Machine Learning to predict later psychosis onset."}], "hero": "https://pe.tedcdn.com/images/ted/2eea2e8d1e96d595fea04ba72f63185b05f30307_2880x1620.jpg", "description": "Can the way you speak and write today predict your future mental state, even the onset of psychosis? In this fascinating talk, neuroscientist Mariano Sigman reflects on ancient Greece and the origins of introspection to investigate how our words hint at our inner lives and details a word-mapping algorithm that could predict the development of schizophrenia. \\"We may be seeing in the future a very different form of mental health,\\" Sigman says, \\"based on objective, quantitative and automated analysis of the words we write, of the words we say.\\"", "tags": ["brain", "cognitive science", "communication", "future", "health", "identity", "language", "mental health", "mind", "neuroscience", "science", "self", "speech", "writing"], "downloads": {"languages": [{"languageCode": "ar", "endonym": "\\u0627\\u0644\\u0639\\